# Reuse Before Create

Before writing a new utility function, always check if an equivalent already exists — especially in `lib/utils.js`.

## Process

1. Search the codebase (particularly `lib/utils.js`) for functions with similar logic or purpose.
2. If a match exists, import and use it. Do not duplicate it locally.
3. If the function is useful beyond a single component, add it to `lib/utils.js` and export it rather than defining it inline.

## Examples

```js
// ❌ BAD — defining a local helper that already exists in lib/utils.js
const formatLocalDate = (date) => {
    if (!date) return '';
    const year = date.getFullYear();
    // ...
};

// ✅ GOOD — import the existing utility
import { formatLocalDateKey } from '@/lib/utils';
```

```js
// ❌ BAD — defining a one-off parser that belongs in lib/utils.js
const parseToLocalDate = (dateStr) => { ... };

// ✅ GOOD — move it to lib/utils.js, export it, and import it
import { parseToLocalDate } from '@/lib/utils';
```
